title: For Sale:  Saiga AK103 Clone 5.5mm Folding Stock 7.62x39
postcontent: Up for sale is an original izhmash new in box unfired saiga 7.62x39 rifle that has been properly converted to the Russian AK-103. The conversion process includes removing the original front hand guard, gas piston guide/gas tube, gas block, and front sight. The barrel is then milled to accept the new style hand guard retainer. The barrel component are then replaced with the proper hand guard retainer,polymer handguards,  gas block, gas tube, and front sight/muzzlebrake with cleaning rod and bayonet attachments. A proper bullet guide has been installed into the front trunnion to allow compatibility with 99% of original AK47 and AKM magazines. The original sporter trigger, trigger guard, bolt hold open, and sporter stock are removed. Once removed, All of the holes in the receiver from the sporterization of the rifle are professionally welded up and ground flush inside and out. The holes for the folding stock latch are cut into the receiver and front trunnion. Once the receiver is ready for reassembly, A brand new original Izhmash 5.5mm rear folding trunnion with either a traingle or polymer stock is hand fitted to the receiver and riveted in. A new Trigger guard is riveted into its proper location.Upon request the rifle will maintain a fixed stock.  A new US made trigger group is installed. The rifle is then completely assembled and function tested. Upon verifying fitment and function of all the parts, the rifle is then detail stripped, ultrasonically cleaned, and professionally cerakoted. The rifle will be shipped in its original factory box. I have quiet a few of these rifles including some slightly used ones(300 rounds or less) I work offshore for 2 weeks at a time so i might not be able to send you more pictures or ship it right away. I accept USPS money orders, cash, and paypal. Buyer pays for shippingKeywords: Arsenal SGL Saiga AK47 AK74 bulgarian izhmash 5.45x39 7.62x39

As it sits, It needs an action retention screw/recoil lug (it is a bolt that acts as both) and a new buttstock. I did fire this when I purchased it this summer, but the stock was too dry and cracked. The fix is simple and will require around $150-175 for the owner to get this old girl up and running. I was saving this for a winter project, but have come into needing funds for a new waterfowl gun.
